{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}} {{Infobox Judge |name = Justice V. R. Krishna Iyer |image = V.R.Krishna Iyer.jpg |birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1915|11|15}} |birth_place = [[Palakkad]], [[Madras Presidency]], [[British India]] |death_date = {{Death date and age|2014|12|04|1915|11|15|df=y}} |death_place = [[cochin]], [[Kerala]], [[India]] |nationality = [[India]]n |residence = [[Ernakulam]], Kerala |spouse = {{marriage| Sarada |1925|1974}} |blank1 = Autobiography |data1 = ''Wandering in Many Worlds'' |Ethnicity = Malayali}}
'''Justice Vaidyanathapuram Rama Iyer Krishna Iyer''' (15 November 1915 &ndash; 4 December 2014) referred to as a conscience keeper of justice in India,<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=http://www.livelaw.in/v-r-krishna-iyer-super-judge/|title=V.R. Krishna Iyer – The Super Judge (1st VRK Memorial Lecture by Fali Nariman)|last=|first=|date=2016-10-28|work=Live Law|access-date=2017-08-06}}</ref> was a visionary and a path-breaking judge, who reformed the Indian criminal justice system with bold changes to jails & police stations, and forged new tools to dispense social justice & justice in the public interest, which stood not just the test of time, but had a profound impact on justice delivery in India in the decades which followed. He pioneered the [[Legal aid|legal-aid]] movement in the country. Before that, he had pioneered land reforms law as a state minister & independent politician, which became a model for the rest of the country.{{cn|date=March 2018}} He stood up for the poor and the underprivileged and was jailed for this once, as an activist lawyer.<ref>{{cite news|title=A voice for the poor and deprived fades away|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/vr-krishna-iyer-19152014/article6662417.ece|accessdate=6 December 2014|work=The Hindu(Kochi Bureau)|date=4 December 2014}}</ref><ref name="express1">{{cite news|last1=Philip|first1=Shaju|title=Former Supreme Court judge V R Krishna Iyer dead|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/2230652former-supreme-court-judge-and-renowned-legal-luminary-v-r-krishna-iyer/|accessdate=6 December 2014|publisher=The Indian Express (Thiruvananthapuram)|date=5 December 2014}}</ref> He zealously guarded human-rights regardless of finding himself isolated.<ref name="Singapore">{{Cite journal|last1=Dam|first1=Shubhankar|title=Criminal Rights and Constitutional Wrongs: A View from India (page 718)|journal=Singapore Academy of Law Journal|publisher=(2013) 25 SAcLJ|pages=714–735|url=http://www.sal.org.sg/digitallibrary/Lists/SAL%20Journal/Attachments/652/%282013%29%2025%20SAcLJ%20714-735%20%28Shubhankar%20Dam%29.pdf#page=5|accessdate=8 December 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219134514/http://www.sal.org.sg/digitallibrary/Lists/SAL%20Journal/Attachments/652/%282013%29%2025%20SAcLJ%20714-735%20%28Shubhankar%20Dam%29.pdf#page=5|archivedate=19 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He was a crusader for social action & the environment,<ref name="Preston">{{cite web|url=http://www.lec.justice.nsw.gov.au/Documents/prestoncj%20krishna%20iyer%20j%20paper%20for%20festschrift.pdf|title=A précis of Justice Krishna Iyer ’s contribution to the environmental jurisprudence of the Supreme Court of India|last1=Preston|first1=Hon. Justice Brian J|date=5 August 2013|website=The Land and Environment Court of New South Wales, Australia|accessdate=7 December 2014}}</ref> and a champion of civil liberties, throughout life. A sports enthusiast and a prolific author,<ref name="many lives">{{cite news|title=The Many Lives of Justice Krishna Iyer|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/The-Many-Lives-of-Justice-Krishna-Iyer/2014/12/05/article2556197.ece|accessdate=8 December 2014|work=The Indian Express|agency=(News Bureau)|date=5 December 2014}}</ref> he was conferred with the [[Padma Vibhushan]] in 1999. Judges in India and around the world continue to cite his judgments in their decisions in court.
==Birth, early life and work in politics== Vaidyanathapuram Rama Ayyar Krishna Iyer was born in 1915 in [[Vaidyanathapuram]] village in [[Palakkad]], which was the part of the then [[Malabar region]] of the then [[Madras]] State, to a lawyer father, named Rama Iyer. He inherited from his father the qualities of taking an avid interest in the community around and using the law for the benefit of those more in need.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/305617907_Balancing_Power_Analysing_Socially_Transformative_Jurisprudence_of_VR_Krishna_Iyer_through_New_Genre_Leadership_Theory|title=Balancing Power: Analysing Socially Transformative Jurisprudence of VR Krishna Iyer through New Genre Leadership Theory (Working Paper)|last=Kylasam Iyer|first=Deepa|last2=Kuriakose|first2=Francis|date=July 2016|website=ResearchGate|language=en|access-date=2017-08-06}}</ref> He studied law from Madras, and started practice in his father's chamber in 1938 at Thalassery, Malabar.<ref name="express1"/> In 1948, when he protested the evil of torture by police for interrogation, he was imprisoned for a month on a fabricated charge of giving legal assistance to communists.<ref name="many lives"/>
He was elected to the Madras Legislative Assembly in 1952, from Thalassery as a non-party, independent candidate.<ref name="express1"/> He became the first minister of law, justice, home, irrigation, power, prisons, social welfare and inland navigation in the first communist government in Kerala headed by [[E. M. S. Namboodiripad]] that came to power in 1957. He initiated legal-aid to the poor, jail reforms incorporating the rights of prisoners, and set up more courts and rescue homes for women and children.<ref name="express1"/><ref name="many lives"/> He got several labour and land reform laws passed. He resolved an inter-state water dispute between the newly formed neighbouring states, Kerala and Tamil Nadu. When this government was dismissed by the central government, he resumed legal practice in August 1959. He lost the 1965 assembly election, which he again contested as an independent candidate.
==Work as a judge== He was appointed a judge of the Kerala High Court in 1968. He was a member of the Law Commission from 1971 to 1973 where he drafted a comprehensive report, which would lead to the [[Legal aid|legal-aid]] movement in the country.<ref name="express1"/> He was elevated as judge of the [http://supremecourtofindia.nic.in/former-justices Supreme Court of India] in 1973.
In June 1975, the Allahabad High Court had unseated Prime Minister Indira Gandhi from the Parliament and barred her from it for another six years. Rebuffing favour-seekers, he heard a challenge to this order in the Supreme Court. He was both blamed for granting a conditional stay and praised for refusing an unconditional stay.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Andhyarujina|first1=T. R.|title=Justice for the helpless|url=http://epaper.indianexpress.com/389864/Indian-Express-Mumbai/06-December-2014#page/13/3|accessdate=10 December 2014|work=The Indian Express|date=6 December 2014}}</ref> Interpreting this as losing the popular mandate to rule, the Opposition called for her resignation. The next day she declared a [[Emergency (India)|state of Emergency]] in the country.<ref>{{cite book|author=Ananth V. Krishna|title=India Since Independence: Making Sense Of Indian Politics|url=https://books.google.com/?id=8v7Vr2iQUHkC&pg=PA149#v=onepage&q&f=true |date=1 September 2011|publisher=Pearson Education India|isbn=978-81-317-3465-0|page=149}}</ref>
A thinker ahead of his time, he would go on to write landmark judgments: * Shamsher Singh case which interpreted the powers of the Cabinet with that of the President. * Maneka Gandhi case which paved the way to read the plain words "right to life" and "personal liberty", to mean [[Fundamental Rights, Directive Principles and Fundamental Duties of India#ManekaCase|many human rights now]], thus expanding Article 21 of the Constitution.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ghouse|first=Mohammud|date=1978|title=Constitutional Rights -1 (Fundamental Rights)|url=http://14.139.60.114:8080/jspui/bitstream/123456789/3328/1/015_1978_Constitutional%20Law-I%20(Fundamental%20Rights).pdf#page=6|journal=Journal of the Indian Law Institute|volume=14|pages=397}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Sudhanshu Ranjan|title=Justice, Judocracy and Democracy in India: Boundaries and Breaches|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Vf4jAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT63#v=onepage&q&f=true|date=21 March 2014|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-317-80977-7|pages=63–}}</ref> That the government of the day cannot put fetters on the rights of citizens,<ref>{{cite web|title=Maneka Gandhi v. Union Of India|url=http://judis.nic.in/supremecourt/imgs1.aspx?filename=5154#page=115|website=(page 115 of 154 - Supreme Court of India)|date=25 January 1978|publisher=[1978 AIR 597] [1978 SCR (2) 621] [1978 SCC (1) 248]|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref> nor, should courts get unduly alarmed,<ref>{{cite web|title=Re: S. Mulgaokar|url=http://judis.nic.in/supremecourt/imgs1.aspx?filename=5128#page=12|website=(page 12 of 28 - Supreme Court of India)|date=21 February 1978|publisher=[1978 AIR 727] [1978 SCR (3) 162] [1978 SCC (3) 339]|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref> when both of them are reacting to a fear of facing all manner of hostile comment, was what he tersely reminded them: {{quote|"Dogs may bark, but the caravan (of justice) passes"||source=}} paraphrasing an immemorial Arab proverb.
* Ratlam Municipality case, where he started a trend for judges to leave the courtroom and go out and see,<ref>{{cite book|author=Sudhanshu Ranjan|title=Justice, Judocracy and Democracy in India: Boundaries and Breaches|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Vf4jAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT69#v=onepage&q&f=true|date=21 March 2014|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-317-80977-7|page=69}}</ref> the situation on the ground.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lec.justice.nsw.gov.au/Documents/prestoncj%20krishna%20iyer%20j%20paper%20for%20festschrift.pdf#page=8|title=A précis of Justice Krishna Iyer’s contribution to the environmental jurisprudence of the Supreme Court of India|last1=Preston|first1=Hon. Justice Brian J|date=5 August 2013|website=The Land and Environment Court of New South Wales, Australia|pages=8|accessdate=7 December 2014}}</ref> Moreover, this case would be a forerunner of cases which would be decided later on, on the concepts of "[[precautionary principle]]", "[[polluter pays]]" and "[[Sustainability|sustainable development]]".<ref name="Greiber2006">{{cite book|author=Thomas Greiber|title=Judges and the Rule of Law: Creating the Links : Environment, Human Rights and Poverty : Papers and Speeches from an IUCN Environmental Law Programme (ELP) Side Event at the 3rd IUCN World Conservation Congress (WCC) Held in Bangkok, Thailand, 17-25 November 2004|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4XRa98xh8T0C&pg=PA28#v=onepage&q&f=true|year=2006|publisher=IUCN|isbn=978-2-8317-0915-4|page=28}}</ref> * Muthamma's case, where he broke through the 'glass ceiling' with gender parity in traditional practices in public employment. * His lonely crusade against the death penalty would later on, make the court impose it only in the "rarest of rare" cases.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lethal Lottery The Death Penalty in India: A study of Supreme Court judgments in death penalty cases 1950-2006 (pages 63-72)|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/documents/asa20/007/2008/en/|pages=1–244|publisher=Amnesty International India and People’s Union for Civil Liberties (Tamil Nadu & Puducherry) May 2008|accessdate=14 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.frontline.in/other/obituary/justice-at-heart/article6719090.ece|title=Justice at heart|last=Venkatesan|first=V.|date=2014-12-24|work=Frontline|access-date=2017-08-06|language=en}}</ref> He brought in safeguards against custodial excesses.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ghouse|first=Mohammud|date=1978|title=Constitutional Rights -1 (Fundamental Rights)|url=http://14.139.60.114:8080/jspui/bitstream/123456789/3328/1/015_1978_Constitutional%20Law-I%20(Fundamental%20Rights).pdf#page=20|journal=Journal of the Indian Law Institute|volume=14|pages=411}}</ref> He made bail conditions humane and directed the government to provide free legal-aid to detainess in prisons facing charges,<ref name="express1"/> once ruling that:<ref>{{cite news|last1=Raghavan|first1=R. K. (former Director, CBI)|title=Reversal of a dangerous trend|url=http://www.thehindu.com/opinion/lead/reversal-of-a-dangerous-trend/article2657012.ece|accessdate=8 December 2014|work=The Hindu|date=26 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title=State of Rajasthan v. Balchand|journal=[1977 Air 2447] [1978 Scr (1) 535] [1977 Scc (4) 308]|date=20 September 1977|pages=1|url=http://judis.nic.in/supremecourt/imgst.aspx?filename=5235|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref>{{quote|"Bail is the rule, and jail, the exception"|}}
Rejecting special courts to try people with influence or "in towers of power" for their excesses, he cautioned against retribution against them in a knee-jerk response, even as he commented on their violations,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://judis.nic.in/supremecourt/imgs1.aspx?filename=4924|title=In Re: The Special Courts Bill, 1978|last=|first=|date=1 Dec 1978|website=Supreme Court of India|pages=66 of 88|access-date=}}</ref> quoting an English verse thus: {{quote|"The law locks up both man and woman, who steals the goose from off the common; But lets the greater felon loose, who steals the common from the goose."}}
He believed in correction and not retribution or vindictiveness in dealing with prisoners. He recommended that meditation methods of Yoga which he practiced, and which he observed in the prisons in the Americas and Oceania, could be introduced in the Indian justice system to help transform not just criminal tendencies in prisoners, but also help judges keep their mental poise invoking their higher values to have a better judgement of a case at hand.<ref>{{cite book|author=V. R. Krishna Iyer|title=Wandering in Many Worlds: An Autobiography|url=https://books.google.com/?id=A4FKhMcmpdQC&pg=PA267#v=onepage&q&f=true|year=2009|publisher=Pearson Education India|isbn=978-81-317-1835-3|pages=267–68}}</ref> He introduced values of international covenants of human rights into Indian jurisprudence.<ref name=":1" /> Outlawing solitary confinement and fetters on prisoners as inhuman, he treated a prisoner’s letter posted from jail as a petition,<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Forster|first1=Christine M. (University of New South Wales, Sydney)|last2=Jivan|first2=Vedna (University of Technology Sydney, Sydney)|title=Public Interest Litigation and Human Rights Implementation: The Indian and Australian Experience (page 16)|url=https://opus.lib.uts.edu.au/research/bitstream/handle/10453/10475/2007005097OK.pdf#page=17|pages=0–32|journal=Asian Journal of Comparative Law|publisher=The Berkeley Electronic Press|year=2008|accessdate=8 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141210072159/https://opus.lib.uts.edu.au/research/bitstream/handle/10453/10475/2007005097OK.pdf#page=17|archive-date=10 December 2014|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref> commenting:<ref name="Singapore" />{{quote|"Freedom behind bars is part of our constitutional tryst...If wars are too important to be left to the generals, surely prisoners’ rights are too precious to be left to the jailors"|}} Along with Justice [[P. N. Bhagwati]], he introduced the concept of [[Public Interest Litigation|PILs (Public Interest Litigations)]] or "people's involvement" in the country's courts with a series of cases.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lec.justice.nsw.gov.au/Documents/prestoncj%20krishna%20iyer%20j%20paper%20for%20festschrift.pdf#page=7|title=A précis of Justice Krishna Iyer ’s contribution to the environmental jurisprudence of the Supreme Court of India|last1=Preston|first1=Hon. Justice Brian J|date=5 August 2013|website=The Land and Environment Court of New South Wales, Australia|pages=7|accessdate=7 December 2014}}</ref> This revolutionary tool, initially used by public-spirited citizens to file PILs on behalf of sections of society unable to on their own, continues to bring in unheard changes in the day-to-day lives of the people even now, decades later.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Andhyarujina|first1=T. R.|title=Disturbing trends in judicial activism|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-opinion/disturbing-trends-in-judicial-activism/article3732377.ece|accessdate=8 December 2014|work=The Hindu|date=6 August 2012}}</ref> Observing this, he states:<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Krishna Iyer|first1=Justice V. R.|title=A democratic demand|journal=Frontline|date=1 February 2003|volume=20|issue=3|url=http://www.frontline.in/static/html/fl2003/stories/20030214003309700.htm|accessdate=10 December 2014}}</ref> {{quote|"To transform the Supreme Court of India into the supreme court for Indians was the challenge...When the history of the judiciary in India comes to be written, PIL will be glorified as the noblest ally of the little Indian"|}}
With an eye on evolving the law for the future, he would often put in a dissenting note in majority judgments, even as he strove for consensus with his brother judges on the bench. Sitting on the bench and away from it, he would reiterate time and again a guiding principle that laws must reflect justice, and justice in turn, must reflect life as lived by the people, stating: {{quote|"The law of all laws is that the 'rule of law' must keep pace with the 'rule of life'"}} by climbing down from its high pedestal, shedding its static and sterile inertia,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Iyer|first1=V. R. Krishna|title=Law and justice in an independent nation|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-opinion/law-and-justice-in-an-independent-nation/article3078643.ece|accessdate=4 November 2015|work=The Hindu|date=21 September 2006}}</ref> to ascertain ground realities for meeting the needs<ref>{{cite web|last=1974 AIR 994|first=1974 SCC (4) 305 (page 8 of 46)|title=State Of Punjab v. Amar Singh|url=http://judis.nic.in/supremecourt/imgs1.aspx?filename=6355#page=8|accessdate=4 November 2015}}</ref> and aspirations of the people in an ever-changing society.<ref>{{cite web|last=1974 AIR 710|first=1974 SCR (2) 282 (page 26 of 38)|title=Baradakanta Mishra vs The Registrar Of Orissa High Court|url=http://judis.nic.in/supremecourt/imgs1.aspx?filename=6417#page=26|accessdate=4 November 2015}}</ref>
==Public life post-retirement and death== He retired as a judge on 14 November 1980 but, continued to advocate the cause of justice, on every forum and through his writings, participating in street protests,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.webindia123.com/news/articles/India/20111211/1889087.html|title=Vaiko shocked over Krishna Iyer's participation in Human Chain stir|last=|first=|date=11 December 2011|website=webindia123.com|access-date=2017-08-07}}</ref> and his house would always remain open, bustling with all who sought his help<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianvanguard.wordpress.com/2008/01/28/keralites-with-bengal-connection-cautioned/|title=Keralites with Bengal connection cautioned|date=2008-01-28|website=Indian Vanguard|access-date=2017-08-06}}</ref> or advice.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Baxi|first1=Upendra|last2=Bhushan|first2=Prashant|title=...their respective articles on Justice Krishna Iyer|url=http://epaper.indianexpress.com/389864/Indian-Express-Mumbai/06-December-2014#page/13/3|accessdate=10 December 2014|work=The Indian Express|date=6 December 2014}}</ref> He stood for the nation's President in 1987, as the Opposition's candidate against R. Venkataraman, the ruling Congress's nominee who won. In 2002, he inquired into the Gujarat riots as part of a citizens' panel, with retired Justice P. B. Sawant among others. He also headed the Kerala Law Reform Commission in 2009. He had been active, almost till a few weeks before his death, when ill-health and advancing age took their toll on him.
He died on 4 December 2014 at the age of 99.<ref>{{cite web|title=Former Supreme Court judge V R Krishna Iyer passes away at 100|url=http://netindian.in/news/2014/12/04/00031722/former-supreme-court-judge-v-r-krishna-iyer-passes-away-100|website=NetIndian|accessdate=4 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/justice-krishna-iyer-passes-away/article6661758.ece | title=Leaving a light, Justice Krishna Iyer passes away | accessdate=4 December 2014}}</ref> and was cremated with state honours. His wife, who would listen to him talk about his work, when on occasion he would change his mind after she gave her opinion on it,<ref name="autobio">{{cite book|author=V. R. Krishna Iyer|title=Wandering in Many Worlds: An Autobiography|url=https://books.google.com/?id=A4FKhMcmpdQC&pg=PA189#v=onepage&q&f=true|year=2009|publisher=Pearson Education India|isbn=978-81-317-1835-3|pages=189}}</ref> had predeceased him.
==Books== He has to his credit 70–100 books, mostly on law, and four travelogues. He has also authored a book in Tamil, ''Neethimandramum Samanvya Manithanum''. ''Leaves from My Personal Life'' is his autobiography.<ref name="autobio"/> There are around five published books by other authors about him.
